              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                Treating liver cancer requires a coordinated effort from a team of specialists. At SALi, our liver cancer program includes hepatologists, surgical oncologists, interventional radiologists, and medical oncologists who work together to create a personalized treatment plan.
              </p>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                Treatment options depend on the stage of the cancer and include liver resection, liver transplantation, ablation, chemoembolization (TACE), and targeted drug therapy. We are at the forefront of liver cancer treatment and research.
              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Understanding Hepatocellular Carcinoma (HCC)</h5>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                Hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) is the most common type of primary liver cancer, accounting for about 75-85% of cases. It typically develops in patients with chronic liver disease or cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, hepatitis C, alcohol-related liver disease, or NAFLD. Early detection and treatment significantly improve outcomes.
              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Risk Factors</h5>
              <ul class="list-items list-unstyled mb-40 pl-40">
                <li>Chronic hepatitis B or C infection</li>
                <li>Liver cirrhosis from any cause</li>
                <li>Heavy alcohol consumption</li>
                <li>Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD/NASH)</li>
                <li>Aflatoxin exposure</li>
                <li>Diabetes and obesity</li>
                <li>Hereditary hemochromatosis</li>
              </ul>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Diagnosis and Staging</h5>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                Diagnosis involves imaging studies (contrast-enhanced CT or MRI), tumor marker testing (AFP - alpha-fetoprotein), and sometimes liver biopsy. We use the Barcelona Clinic Liver Cancer (BCLC) staging system to determine the best treatment approach. Early-stage tumors may be curable with surgery or transplantation.
              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Treatment Options</h5>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                <strong>Surgical Resection:</strong> Removal of the tumor and surrounding tissue in patients with preserved liver function and early-stage disease.
              </p>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                <strong>Liver Transplantation:</strong> Best option for small tumors meeting Milan criteria (single tumor ≤5cm or up to 3 tumors ≤3cm each) with underlying cirrhosis.
              </p>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                <strong>Ablation Therapy:</strong> Radiofrequency ablation (RFA) or microwave ablation destroys small tumors using heat energy.
              </p>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                <strong>Trans-Arterial Chemoembolization (TACE):</strong> Delivers chemotherapy directly to the tumor while blocking its blood supply, effective for intermediate-stage HCC.
              </p>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                <strong>Targeted Therapy and Immunotherapy:</strong> Systemic medications like sorafenib, lenvatinib, and immunotherapy combinations for advanced disease.
              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Surveillance and Prevention</h5>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                Patients with cirrhosis or chronic hepatitis B should undergo regular surveillance with ultrasound and AFP testing every 6 months. Prevention includes hepatitis B vaccination, antiviral treatment for hepatitis B and C, alcohol abstinence, maintaining healthy weight, and managing metabolic risk factors.
              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Our LICAP Program</h5>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
